korean:
  title: 사견방
  author: 임춘
  language: kor
  text: |-
    장마비 뒤의 장안에
    나를 생각해 멀리 찾아왔네 그려
    이 적막한 달팽이집 앞에
    머무른 사마 수레
    항상 굶주리는 궁한 두자미
    참 병 아닌 유마거사(당(唐) 시인 왕유(王維))
    문간에 이름을 적지 말고 가소
    세상에 이 내 명성이 더욱 날까 두렵네
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0120_010_0290&viewSync=OT
  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 항상 굶주리는 궁한 두자미(杜子美) : '
    value: 두보(杜甫). 그의 시에, “항상 굶은 어린 자식 안색이 처량하다.”[恒飢稚子色凄凉]한 것이 있다.
english:
  title: In Response to a Visit
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    After the long rains in Chang'an,
    you have come seeking me from afar, it seems.
    Before this lonely snail's cottage
    your four-horse carriage lingers.

    I endure hunger like Du Fu in his poverty,
    not afflicted like old Vimalakīrti with feigned illness.
    I beg you—inscribe no name upon my gate,
    fearing my reputation will only grow the more.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Du Fu (杜甫), the Tang poet, was known for his works expressing hardship and hunger during times of poverty.
  - key: ''
    value: Vimalakīrti (維摩) was a Buddhist lay follower known for his miraculous feigned illness in Buddhist scripture, often referenced in Chinese poetry as a model of spiritual cultivation.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'four-horse carriage' suggests the visitor's high status or official position, contrasting with the speaker's humble dwelling.
